		<hotspot name="info1" style="skin_info_hotspotstyle" ath="0" atv="0" info_title="The Origins of the Grid" info_text="Before the era of bespoke, factory-built racing machines, early British motorsport was born on the public roads. The 1922 Raleigh 350cc (2¾ hp) is a perfect representation of this grassroots era. Built with a robust side-valve engine, a Sturmey-Archer gearbox, and a utilitarian flat-tank frame, it was designed as an economical, everyday workhorse. It was precisely these types of reliable, mass-market motorcycles that early enthusiasts modified, tested in reliability trials, and eventually pushed to their limits on dirt tracks, laying the essential engineering and cultural foundations for modern circuits." />

	</scene>

